occurrences.line_text: In prime of youthly yeares, when corage hot
The knight was fiers, and full of youthly heat:
Old Timon, who in youthly yeares hath beene
It was in freshest flowre of youthly yeares,
And deckt himselfe with feathers youthly gay,
Aboue the reason of her youthly yeares:
Therein haue I spent all my youthly daies,
For the braue youthly Champions to assay,
And with him led to sea an youthly trayne,
Did all that youthly rout so much appall,
There on a day a noble youthly knight
Wretchedly wearing out his youthly yeares,
And being fresh and full of youthly spright,
In prime of youthly yeares, when first the flowre
Vnto your patience, ne be ill ypaid;
He clothed was, ypainted full of eyes;
Farre vnderneath a craggie clift ypight,
His life was nigh vnto deaths doore yplast,
Sir Guyon mindfull of his vow yplight,
And were I not, yet is my trouth yplight,
That hath thee hither brought to taste mine yre?
Therewith redoubled was his raging yre,
And fild her hidden caues with stormie yre,
Who all enrag'd with smart and franticke yre,
So flam'd his eyne with rage and rancorous yre:
And shortly ouertooke: I breathing yre,
That welnigh molt his hart in raging yre,
The cause of their dissention and outrageous yre.
Gnawing her nayles for felnesse and for yre,
Beare off the burden of her raging yre;
Nought may abide the tempest of his yre,
But she backstarting with disdainefull yre,
Tell me what worlds despight, or heauens yre
And with his dreadfull instrument of yre,
Fearelesse of foes, or fortunes wrackfull yre,
Then all the stormes of fortunes former yre
Which he had spilt, and all to rags yrent,
His goodly corps on ragged cliffs yrent,
She flong, and her faire deawy lockes yrent,
That all his mayle yriv'd, and plates yrent,
That at the length he has yrent the dore,
That all his mayle yriv'd, and plates yrent,
It yrkes me, leaue thee in this wofull state,
Yrkesome of life, and too long lingring night.
One day nigh wearie of the yrkesome way,
He therein saw that yrkesome sight, which smote
Were yrkesome to report; yet that foule Beast
Sayd Calidore ; Now sure it yrketh mee,
Hauing yrockt a sleepe his irkesome spright,
And the sharpe yron did for anger eat,
So bent his speare, and spurnd his horse with yron heele.
With thrilling point of deadly yron brand,
The yron walles to ward their blowes are weake & fraile.
And heaped blowes like yron hammers great:
Before the dore her yron charet stood,
Then to her yron wagon she betakes,
With which her yron wheeles did them affray,
Chattring their yron teeth, and staring wide
Wyld beasts in yron yokes he would compell;
As when that diuelish yron Engin wrought
An yron brest, and backe of scaly bras,
The yron rowels into frothy fome he bit.
And in my heart his yron arrow steepe,
At last he came vnto an yron doore,
Which shaking off, he rent that yron dore,
Deepe written in my heart with yron pen,
And bitter Penance with an yron whip,
Three ranckes of yron teeth enraunged were,
Vpon his crest the hardned yron fell,
And clapt his yron wings, as victor he did dwell.
That glauncing fire out of the yron plaid;
And bound him hand and foote with yron chains.
And on his shield like yron sledges bet:
Thereon an yron lock did fasten firme and strong.
And both his feet in fetters to an yron racke.
With hundred yron chaines he did him bind,
Yet his great yron teeth he still did grind,
Tho hurling high his yron braced arme,
Captiu'd eternally in yron mewes,
Deepe in their flesh, quite through the yron walles,
Your yron brestes, or pittie could find place,
His yron coate all ouergrowne with rust,
The one in hand an yron whip did straine,
Did alwayes sore, beating his yron wings;
But huge great yron chests and coffers strong,
Till that they came vnto an yron dore,
With yron toungs, and sprinckled oft the same
In his right hand an yron club he held,
And him so sore smote with his yron mace,
And there such ghastly noise of yron chaines,
The one of yron, the other of bright gold,
She caught in hand an huge great yron mace,
He reard him vp, and loosd his yron bands,
It is not yron bandes, nor hundred eyes,
Of such deceipt, kept th'yron dore fast bard,
Another yron dore, on which was writ,
With which that yron wicket open flew,
And her small wast girt round with yron bands,
And did his yron brond so fast applie,
Of many yron hammers beating ranke,
But to small purpose yron wedges made;
Vpon his headpeece with his yron mall;
A paire of redwhot yron tongs did take
What yron courage euer could endure,
And sure had not his massie yron mace
And gnasht his yron tuskes at that displeasing sight.
That neither yron barres, nor brasen locke
An yron man, which did on her attend
His name was Talus, made of yron mould,
Who in his hand an yron flale did hould,
His yron page, who him pursew'd so light,
And layd on load with his huge yron flaile,
Remaines on earth, preseru'd from yron rust
But that great yron groome, his gard and gouernment.
Who with few sowces of his yron flale,
Those yron fetters, wherewith he was gyu'd,
And euery while that mighty yron man,
With his great yron sledge doth strongly on it beat.
As if she had an yron anduile beene,
He with his yron flaile amongst them thondred,
Cold yron chaines, with which let him be tide;
And many yron bands on him to lade.
The yron man, albe he wanted sence
Ah wellaway (sayd then the yron man,)
With his rude yron flaile, they gan to flie,
But chiefly by that yron page he ghest,
But when they of that yron man had told,
He with his yron flale did thresh so thin,
She for that yron prison did enquire,
With yron wheeles and hookes arm'd dreadfully,
The yron charet, and the wheeles did teare,
Amongst the yron hookes and graples keene,
Whose top was arm'd with many an yron hooke,
Which when he saw, his yron man he sent,
Haue turn'd himselfe, he with his yron flayle
With a strong yron chaine and coller bound,
That any yron eyes to see it would agrize.
And with his huge great yron axe gan hew
Backe to recule; vntill that yron man
But chiefly Talus with his yron flayle,
Nathlesse the yron man did still pursew
All armed in a cote of yron plate,
Whose steale was yron studded, but not long,
That through the yron walles their way they rent,
And did his yron axe so nimbly wield,
And that same yron man which could reueale
Would her haue chastiz'd with his yron flaile,
That yron heart it hardly could sustaine:
All night in darkenesse, duld with yron rust,
Made all of rusty yron, ranckling sore,
And in his hand a mighty yron club he bore.
And with his yron batton, which he bore,
And with his yron club to ground him strooke;
In yron chaines, of liberty bereft,
But with his yron club preparing way,
All set with yron teeth in raunges twaine,
Of surest yron, made with many a lincke;
Against his will fast bound in yron chaine,
Or fault of men, he broke his yron chaine,
Disarmed all of yron-coted Plate,
Through working of the stone therein yset.
Yshrowded was, and euery mortall wight
Whiles the cold ysickles from his rough beard,
He is yslaine, which is the ground of all our woe.
Soone as the cruell flames yslaked were,
Doth light the lower world, were halfe yspent,
She forth yssew'd out of her loathed bowre,
Yt nought too deare I deemd, while so my dear I sought.
Yt framed was of precious yuory,
Yt seemd th'enchaunted flame, which did CreÃ¼sa wed.
Ythrild with deepe disdaine of his proud threat,
As one whose inner parts had bene ythrild
But none more piteous euer was ytold,
Disshiuered speares, and shields ytorne in twaine,
Such helplesse harmes yts better hidden keepe,
Where ease abounds, yt's eath to doe amis;
Whilst freshest Flora her with Yuie girlond crownd.
And on his head an yuie girland had,
And with an yuie twyne his wast is girt about.
Framed of wanton Yuie, flouring faire,
Enchaced with a wanton yuie twine.
A trayle of yuie in his natiue hew:
Would surely deeme it to be yuie trew:
With wanton yuie twyne entrayld athwart,
His wast was with a wreath of yuie greene
He backe returning by the Yuorie dore,
Of turtle doues, she sitting in an yuorie chaire.
With princely gifts of yuorie and gold,
And th'yuorie in golden mantle gownd:
Gold, amber, yuorie, perles, owches, rings,
Dropped adowne vpon her yuorie brest:
Whose yuorie shoulders weren couered all,
Her yuorie necke, her alablaster brest,
The one faire fram'd of burnisht Yuory,
In yuory sheath, ycaru'd with curious slights;
That her became, as polisht yuory,
Yt framed was of precious yuory,
That seemd the waues were into yuory,
Or yuory into the waues were sent;
Was all abasht, and her pure yuory
And all the others pauement were with yuory spilt.
Like the faire yuory shining they did see,
Vpon her yuory forehead that same day
Chaunst to espy vpon her yuory chest
Which being all with Yuy ouerspred,
To saueguard her, ywandred all alone;
A right good knight, and true of word ywis:
Not this the worke of womans hand ywis,
That shall I you recount (quoth he) ywis,
With flashing thunderbolt ywounded sore:
Or wrath of cruell wight on thee ywrake?
And that her sacred Booke, with bloud ywrit,

But when their bootlesse zeale she did restraine
But that with constant zeale, and courage bold,

But since thy faithfull zeale lets me not hyde
With great deuotion, and with litle zeale:
And full of fiery zeale, him followed long,
Caried with feruent zeale, ne did he ceasse,
Full inly sorie for the feruent zeale,
Or zeale of friends combynd with vertues meet.
And flam'd with zeale of vengeance inwardly,
For zeale of Iustice was against her bent.
For deare affection and vnfayned zeale,
Each others griefe with zeale affectionate,
And zealous hast away is quickly gone
Your zealous hast, till morrow next againe
Which in their spirits kindling zealous fire,
That after him he ran with zealous haste,
His name was Zele, that him right well became,
To all assayes; his name was called Zele:
Strongly did Zele her haynous fact enforce,
Which when as Zele perceiued to abate,
Then Zele began to vrge her punishment,
With zelous enuy of Greekes cruell fact,
The whiles sweet Zephirus lowd whisteled
That when myld Zephyrus emongst them blew,
